With the above optimization parameters, the fluorescence response of RFP to different concentrations of AO was tested. As illustrated in Fig. 3
                        A, the fluorescence intensity of the emission peak of RFP at 436 nm decreased significantly with the increase of AO concentration in the range of 0.0–40.0 μM. Conversely, the fluorescence intensity of RFP at 592 nm exhibited stability. The inset of Fig. 3A illustrated a clear color change in RFP from pink to red to orange as AO concentration increased. Fig. 3B showed a favorable linear relationship (R2 = 0.992) between I0/I and the target concentration (0.01–10.0 μM), and the linear fit yields the regression equation I0/I = 0.104[C]+1.0279. The LOD was as low as 12.3 nM on a 3σ/KSV (n = 10) basis where σ denotes the standard deviation of the measured signal of the blank sample and the KSV denotes the slope of the standard curve. Noteworthy, the LOD achieved by RFP was lower than those reported for various AO detection strategies (Table 1
                        ), indicating the feasibility of further application to real samples. The sensor showed a good LOD and can be used as a highly accurate and sensitive AO detection tool.

Food and drug samples such as scutellaria powder, pollen typhae, corydalis tuber, curry power, bean curb and lemon candy were selected to verify the feasibility of this ratiometric fluorescent sensor to identify AO in real samples. Multiple 2.0 mL of RFP solutions were prepared, sample extracts (20.0 μL) were added individually and mixed thoroughly, and fluorescence intensities of the RFP solutions at 436 and 592 nm (λ
                        ex = 400 nm) were measured and I0/I was computed. The average recoveries of the spiked samples were 96.7–113.8% at added concentrations of 0.1, 0.2 and 0.3 μM, with relatively low RSD values of 0.92–2.37%. Meanwhile, the content of AO in actual samples was analyzed using HPLC, and chromatograms and linear curves were shown in Fig. S4 and compared with the prepared RFP sensor (Table 2
                        ). The results showed that the RFP-based fluorescence method was consistent with the analytical results of high-performance liquid chromatography (HPLC).
